etical metaphor that enables a hyperbolic re-narrativization of modern historicity. Du Bois thus emerges as an exemplary thinker of history and hope for the world beyond the limit of the present.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aDu Bois, W. E. B. (William Edward Burghardt), 1868-1963--Criticism and interpretation. 0aDu Bois, W. E. B. (William Edward Burghardt), 1868-1963. Color and democracy. 0aDu Bois, W. E. B. (William Edward Burghardt), 1868-1963. World and Africa. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848420440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438484204423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438484204/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles